class Solution {
public:
    int largestRectangleArea(vector<int>& heights) {

        stack<int> aStack;

        int aResult = 0;
        for (int i=0;i<=heights.size();i++) {

            int aCurrentHeight = i < heights.size() ? heights[i] : 0;

            if (aStack.empty() || aCurrentHeight >= heights[aStack.top()]) {
                aStack.push(i);
            } else {
                int aTop = aStack.top(); aStack.pop();
                int aHeight = heights[aTop];

                int aSpan = aStack.empty() ? i : (i - (aStack.top() + 1));
                int aArea = aSpan * aHeight;

                aResult = max(aResult, aArea);

                i -= 1;
            }
        }
        return aResult;
    }
};
```

This is one way to construct the loop which reduces duplicate code...

Basically, once you start decreasing in height, you can walk backwards to something of lower height. You will move forward if you can achieve taller height than the current top of the stack. This functions sort of like a sliding window, which optimizes area.

